arch:property.oc:show_val: Locus 7 consists of all the soil, artifacts and architectural fragments between the bottom of Locus 5 and the ceramic tile floor. In this locus were found the fallen column drums and arch stones that clearly show the collapse of the cryptoporticus and colonnade. On at least one occasion, arch stones were found lying in where they had fallen on the ceramic tile floor, directly in a line with their former positions. Even though Locus 7 encompasses more than one half-meter deep band of excavation across the trench, it did not change with depth, and was therefore considered one locus. It is not noticeably different from Locus 5, and should therefore be combined with it.

XI
Phase XII: Robbing and abandonment continue.
Phase XI: Further collapse post-CE 5th c. Possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512.
XII

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of the south gallery cryptoporticus of the Propylaeum West. The temple north colonnade falls from south to north across the Propylaeum, damage is incurred on the Propylaeum Retaining Wall and the entire area is overburdened with soil and debris.
Opening elevation: NW: 894.452 m; NE: 894.472 m; SW: 894.622 m; SE: 894.472 m.
Closing elevation: NW: 893.349 m; NE: 892.511 m, SW: 893.432 m, SE: 893.092 m.

Phase VI: Late Nabataean ca. 106 CE period of minor collapse and repairs. Collapse of the south gallery cryptoportici of the Propylaeum East and West. Signs of Roman aggression noted particularly in the north gallery of the Propylaeum West, which was used as a repository for ballista balls against threatening forces.

19.50 m total east west, bottom half meter stopped at 15.25 m from Locus 4 to enable soil dumping from Trench 81. 4.39 m north south in most of the trench, 5.30 m north south in the doorway in the west, narrower at the bottom where bounded by the bench.
X
Stage 4/5
Ballista repository, with stone ballista balls, found embedded in the gray mortar subfloor (Locus 23) in the north gallery west and in the overlying soil fill. More than 50 in number.
IX
VI
Bottom layer of fill in the Northwest Corridor

Abandonment and destruction. The doorway to Propylaeum West Room 1 is blocked and the room is abandoned. The arch system of the south gallery cryptoporticus collapses, fill accumulates and the columns of the north colonnade fall.
Stage 6
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th through 5th c.
